Join Adam Grubb, Director of Very Edible Gardens and co-author ofÿThe Weed Forager?s Handbook, for a fascinating walk on the wild side, foraging for edible weeds. Note: Children are most welcome (please register for them too) although they must be accompanied by an adult who takes full responsibility for what they eat - and what they don't - during (and after!) the course. name__text: Darebin Repair Cafe #7 Our first birthday!
description__text: Darebin Repair cafe #7 will be at 220 High St Preston. Our 7th Repair cafe is our first birthday and we are back where we kicked off in May 2018 at The Bridge, Preston.ÿ Bring your item requiring repair to the Darebin Repair Cafe and our community of fixers will repair it. You sit with your personal 'fixer' and explain what is wrong with your item so you can learn how to repair it again in the future. The Moon Rabbit Cafe will be open on the day for your snack and coffee needs for purchasing.  Repair Cafes are a worldwide movement to challenge designÿobsolescenceÿand share fixing skills within our community. Fixing, instead of throwing out and purchasing another item saves resources and keeps skills in our community alive.Repairs on: bicycles, jewellery, shoes,general, glueing, darning, clothes, small machines, toys.  What to do - 1. Book a time slot here on eventbrite. 2. Email us with information on the item including photo and manual if available to ÿtransitiondarebin@gmail.com. 3. Turn up on the day. (come early, so there is time to look over your item)  Note - we may not always be able to repair an item - but best efforts will be made. If you know what parts are needed - please provide them on the day.  Pre-booking is essential as places are limited. People living in the council area of Darebin will be given first priority for tickets.   For more information on the session or if you can provide volunteer assistance on the day - Contact Transitiondarebin@gmail.com  We are kindly supported by the City of Darebin.  For more information on Repair Cafes and the International Repair Cafe Foundation that we are affiliated with - seeÿhttps://repaircafe.org/en/  Repair Cafes are a great way to connect with others in your community and build your skills. We are keen to hear If you would like to register as a fixer or provide some assistance with the many and varied jobs on the day likeÿsetting up, packing up, ushering, tea/coffee, baking, administrative tasks such as registration, weighing, photography, handing out and collection of waiver forms etc.ÿ  Note - by purchasing a ticket, you are agreeing to be added to Transition Darebin's mailing list where we will send you occasional emails on upcoming events and items of interest happening within the council area of Darebin and surrounds.
summary: Darebin Repair cafe #7 will be at 220 High St Preston. Our 7th Repair cafe is our first birthday and we are back where we kicked off in Ma

name__text: Olives to Oil Harvesting Party - Hawthorn
description__text: Olives to Oil is an annual celebration that brings communities together in the name of sustainable olive oil. People come together to harvest unwanted olives from Melbourne backyards and street trees to be pressed into local olive oil to take home for free. Come along to this event either to drop off some olives you've already picked on the 25th May, or to join our "harvsting party". We'll send you out with a map and harvesting equipment to go and pick local olive trees. The olives you pick will be pressed into olive oil which is free for you to collect the following weekend - imagine - your own Hawthorn Olive Oil! Please arrive prompty at 2pm so you can receive your map and harvesting equipment. Wear walking shoes and dress for the weather.  If you have an olive tree in mind and just want to drop off your olives - head toÿhttps://3000acres.org/olives-to-oil-2019/ÿto learn more or email us at hello@3000acres.org.
summary: Olives to Oil is an annual celebration that brings communities together in the name of sustainable olive oil. People come together to harves

name__text: Photographic Thoughtflow Sessions & Lecture with Tony Hewitt Melbourne
description__text: It's that time of year again! With awards season in full swing, we've joined forces with the best in the industry to give you a day of invaluable information from one of our very own prestigious ambassadors.ÿ    We all have our own way of seeing, and in the world of creative image making it seems everyone is looking for the 'Edge' that will help our images stand out from others. Whatever genre you choose to photograph, your personal signature and style is something that is unique to you. Understand and recogniseÿthe value of your personal style and challenge yourself to take your style to the next level.     40 Minute Day Sessions - 12 pm - 4:40 pm A unique opportunity to learn close up with Tony where he will share in the basic Thoughtflow and Workflowÿbehind his image preparation for various outcomes including, image preparation for Awards & Exhibitions, and some Creative and Practical techniques.You'll learn:  Image editing techniques to take your images from the interesting to the extraordinary How to format your image to suit the intended output, whether it's print competitions, exhibitions, books & magazines, or online.  *Maximum one session per person. Please do not book multiple sessions. 2 Hour Evening Talk - 6:30 pm -8:30 pm The Power of Personal ProjectsJoin us at 6:30 pm as Tony leads you on an inspirational journey through some of his personal projects.In a world saturated by image making, we are often challenged as photographers and business people to find individuality, purpose and direction. Personal Projects have the power help us discover not only our true potential, but also what it is that brings out the best of who we are as image makers, and where we can create the greatest difference. AIPP Grand Master Tony Hewitt will share his experience and learnings from some of his most successful personal projects, including fulfilling a lifelong dream that resulted in one of the biggest photographic projects ever undertaken in Australia.ÿSpots are limited and bookings are essential. There are 4 tickets available per session - book your spot today. About Tony Hewitt - Tony Hewitt is an internationally recognised, multiple award-winning landscape photographer based in Perth.He has explored the genres of Fine Art Photography, Landscape, Portrait and Commercial, and has been exhibited both locally and internationally.Tony is a ?Grand Master of Photography? and Honorary Fellow of the AIPP, and a Fellow of the NZIPP.ÿhttp://www.tonyhewitt.com/
summary: It's that time of year again! With awards season in full swing, we've joined forces with the best in the industry to give you a day of inv

name__text: **SOLD OUT** Younghusband Tour ? from wool store to beautiful industrial village
description__text: As part of the Australian Heritage Festival, explore Kensington?s impressive 19th-century industrial Younghusband woolstore precinct on a guided tour and discover its unique past, present and future. Be part of the Younghusband story as it embarks on a rejuvenation process to become a diverse urban village that celebrates the site's heritage. On the Kensington railway stands Younghusband, an impressive collection of industrial red brick buildings spanning two blocks, connected by a bluestone laneway. Once a wool store and now home to some of Melbourne?s most creative businesses and artists ? the historical warehouse built in 1906 is again being reimagined. Over the next five years, Impact Investment Group will transform the precinct into a beautiful industrial village for the common good, with an eclectic mix of values aligned tenants including government, corporates, artists, makers, hospitality and e-commerce businesses. Working with leading architects Woods Bagot, IIG aims for the Younghusband project to demonstrate how a heritage industrial area can be revitalised with a deep commitment to the principles of sustainability, heritage, collaboration and community. Visitors will be inspired by vast open spaces filled with natural light filtered through the sawtooth roof, original timber floors, iron beams and exposed brick.
summary: As part of the Australian Heritage Festival, explore Kensington?s impressive 19th-century industrial Younghusband woolstore precinct on a gu

name__text: Jells Park Photo Walk :: In the Footsteps of Clarice Beckett
description__text: Clarise Beckett was a tonalist painter, in the Max Meldrum tradition, who painted many works around Beaumaris. Her work may not be widely known but embraced many aspects of tonalism, minimalism in a modernist way. This walk will visit places both she and the Heildelberg School Impressionists painted and look at tonal balance in the way a photo can be composed. Hopefully you?ll also get a chance to photograph a variety of water birds, beach scenes and some traditional (less colourful) beach boxes. ?A painter should begin every canvas with a wash of black, because all things in nature are dark except where exposed by the light.?ÿ ?ÿLeonardo da Vinci
